#ChisholmBluestreaks Fall Sports Update: The MSHSL has made the following decision about fall sports.

1. Volleyball and football seasons have been moved to the spring starting approx March 15.

2. Regular spring sports (fastpitch, baseball, and track) will begin May 15 and go into July.

3. Remaining regular fall sports (swimming and cross country) will proceed as normal but with limitations. This also includes our co-op sports with Hibbing (soccer and tennis).

Monday, August 17th will be the first day of fall sports practice. Now is a good time to start thinking about the registration process. You can do it online through the RSchool program. That link is on the Chisholm Schools website. You may also pick up the paper packets from the high school office.

#ChisholmBluestreaks Parents, Guardians, and Students:

Please remember to take time to read the rough draft of all 3 scenarios that are being considered for our fall reopening on our district website and complete the survey.

There will be a special board meeting Wednesday, August 5, 2020 at 5 pm. This will be a virtual meeting and the link will be posted on the website. We will be presenting the plans and the board will decide which plan to use to open this fall. We need your input to give the board the best information we can.

Thank you for your patience in this process. Know that the safety of our students and staff come first in our decision making.

https://www.chisholm.k12.mn.us/restart-plan-f5166679

For many years, at the end of the school year Mrs. Nehiba and her first graders have invited their families and school staff to their classroom for a Literature Show.

Students would read and share books and reports they had written throughout the year. This year, due to distance learning, their Literature Show took place through a google meet and students submitted photos of their creations.

Here are some of the photos they sent in and some photos taken earlier in the year. Fortunately, students were able to share some of their work before distance learning began. What awesome authors and illustrators! <3 #ChisholmBluestreaks

post_text:
Congratulations to Jonah Giermann and Tiahna Brayton!! They were selected by the #ChisholmBluestreaks coaches as our 2020 Chisholm Athletes of the Year.

As a result of winning these prestigious awards, they will both receive $250 scholarships from the local Chisholm Legion Post 247.

Tiahna was involved in 4 sports throughout her career: Volleyball, Cheerleading, Track, and Softball. She was named to the Volleyball 2019 Northern Lakes all conference team and 2019 IRC all conference honorable mention this past year.

Jonah Giermann was involved in 3 sports - Cross Country, Swimming, & Track. He was nominated and received the 2020 Regional Triple A award - one of the most honorable awards for an athlete in the state of MN. He was also a top 10 finalist for the award at the state level.

This is free for every student whether they purchased a yearbook or not.

Get started here:
yearbooksigning.jostens.com

post_text:
In the fall, Mrs. Jensen's class went on a field trip to her house to explore her garden. It was mostly vegetables, but one student asked why she had so many marigolds. She answered that they help keep bugs off the plants. It seemed like everyone wanted a marigold after that!

For an end of the year project, Mrs. Jensen's students have been having a "seed race." They planted marigold seeds (from Mrs. Jensen's garden) and sunflower seeds and have been studying which seed grows the fastest in the same conditions. They've been recording data and making comparisons.

Now they're hoping for warm weather so they can replant their plants soon! #ChisholmBluestreaks

post_text:
We're back with another story from our #ChisholmBluestreaks Spanish students. üìñ

The Poor Old Lady (La Pobre viejecita) is a fairy tale, best known in Latin America. It tells the story of a rich old lady who has everything (clothes, goods, food.). However, in each verse of the story she is described as someone who complains about having nothing. At the end, the poor old lady dies from all the alleged complications which she had.

Mrs. Jensen's fifth graders built bridges as a #STEM activity recently. Aiden decided he wanted to use what he's learned from welding to make a bridge for this project. He measured the metal, cut it out, and welded it together! He enjoyed building this bridge with his dad.

Aiden tested tools, a pressure washer, and even himself to see if the bridge would hold up under the weight. It did! üòÉ

Way to go, Aiden! Awesome work! #ChisholmBluestreaks

post_text:
Mrs. Jensen has been having fun with her 5th graders. This week, they tried creating art on their heads. To play, first students put a paper plate on their heads. They listened as Mrs. Jensen read a wacky list of directions and tried to draw the pictures. They drew a spring picture with a sun, flowers and birds followed by a camping picture with trees, tent and a campfire. It wasn't as easy as it sounds! ;)

To wrap up class, students had fun introducing their furry friends (and little brothers). <3 #ChisholmBluestreaks

What a week, and what creative kids! <3 #WeGotThis #ChisholmBluestreaks

post_text:
#ChisholmBluestreaks families: Have you tried number puzzles with your child(ren)?

This is an activity our 1st graders completed when school was in session, but it would be easy to replicate at home! Find a picture (print one from the internet or use a photograph, coloring page, or picture from a magazine). Cut the picture into strips and label the bottom of each piece in a counting pattern appropriate for your child (count by 1s, 2s, 5s, 10s, etc). The child finds the counting pattern and lines the strips up to reveal the complete picture! :)

#ChisholmBluestreaks Parents, Guardians, and Caregivers:

We know you are as overwhelmed as we are right now. We as a community are navigating uncharted waters. We want you to know that the school is supporting you as you are supporting us. We want you to know if you need to talk to us, please do. If you get overwhelmed with an assignment or the whole situation, reach out to us. Contact the teacher or the administrator: We want to support you in these waters.

Chisholm High School has started a theme that we want you to share with us. #WeGotThis. In the spirit of pulling together, our staff has been making paper hearts of all colors and sizes to hang in the windows to show our community that we are in this together and we will get through this. <3

Next week, we'll be sending hearts with our #WeGotThis message home with students receiving meals to decorate and hang in their windows. Please feel free to make your own hearts to display in your homes/businesses!

Thank you for all you are doing to keep our students and community safe. <3

Parents or Guardians Chisholm School District 695: Don't forget to call to schedule your appointment for our Early Childhood Screening on April 3, 2020. This is for children ages 3¬Ω to 5 years old who are not yet in kindergarten.

Please call (218) 254-5726 ext 1902 to set up an appt.

Early Childhood Screening is a quick and simple check of how
your child is growing and developing. Screening can detect possible health or learning concerns, so that children can get help before they start school. The start of kindergarten is an important time of rapid learning and growth.

In order for your child to start kindergarten in any Minnesota public school, your child needs to have an Early Childhood Screening! Early Childhood Screening is free and this is NOT registration for kindergarten. #ChisholmBluestreaks

Congratulations to our newest CHS Students of the Week: Marina and Aaliyah!

Marina is a senior. She was nominated by Mrs. Tomczak, who said: ‚ÄúMarina is new to the school and the area this year but it has not stopped her from doing as much as she can. She is very active in school and after school clubs all the while keeping up with her school work. She always has a smile and is willing to help others no matter what she is doing. Marina is wonderful to have in class and will be missed next year.‚Äù

Aaliyah is a 10th grade student. She was nominated by Mrs. Esler. Mrs. Esler said, ‚ÄúAaliyah has made remarkable gains in the last 5 weeks of completing her work and passing her classes. She has changed her attitude around from not wanting to do anything to grumbling about it, but doing it anyway. She does have a smile every day for me, even when she tries to ignore me. Keep up the positive change and passing those classes.‚Äù

post_text:
Chisholm Bluestreak parents,

The news is full of stories stressing the need to be prepared for a time when serious illness reaches our area, in case we have to close public buildings like our school.
This last summer Education Minnesota, working with the Administration and School Board Members, put together an E-Learning plan. This plan allows schools to close the physical building, but have students attending school through a digital format. This enables the school to continue the education of your students.
Today, when you are meeting with teachers, please ask about their e-learning plan. The Plan has 7-12 students using their Chromebooks and K-6 teachers have a rubric for the students to follow to complete their work.

Thank you,
Dr. Janey Blanchard
Superintendent

post_text:
Students at Chisholm Elementary recently participated in the Great Backyard Bird Count! This annual, global, citizen science event is sponsored by the National Audubon Society & Cornell Lab of Ornithology.

Through Chisholm School's Dimensions Program, students were introduced to The Great Backyard Bird Count data collection process and to bird identification methods. Then, over President's Day weekend, the students watched birds in their backyards, our communities, and our northwoods, tallying them by species, number of individuals, location, and time of day.

Finally, they submitted their collected data into The Great Backyard Bird Count/eBird database, which will help scientists study trends in bird populations all over the world. Our students identified 14 different species and tallied 438 individual birds! :D #ChisholmBluestreaks

post_text:
Checking in with an update from #JensensJanuary! Mrs. Jensen's 5th graders did so much reflecting during January! These Super Stars made New Year‚Äôs goals - not just resolutions! They learned more about having a #GrowthMindset, created a very fruitful classroom tree for positive feelings and choices to go along with their goals for reading, learning, working harder and ways to show love, compassion and kindness.

<3 Our attitudes can make the world a better place! <3

The students learned about Martin Luther King Jr., Ruby Bridges, Rosa Parks, and current events. They drew pictures of MLK Jr. making his "I Have a Dream" speech, watched videos about his speeches, and shared their own dreams for a brighter and kinder future!

It was an awesome month, and Mrs. Jensen is so proud of all they accomplished! #ChisholmBluestreaks

post_text:
It's time again to celebrate our newest CHS Students of the Week: Bella and Aiperi!

Bella is a 9th grade student. She was nominated by Mrs. Yuretich, who said: ‚ÄúBella not only shows an excellent work ethic, working hard in class every day, but also displays an exemplary character, showing kindness and compassion to others.‚Äù

Aiperi is a senior at CHS. She was nominated by Ms. Lubovich. Ms. Lubovich said: ‚ÄúWhat an experience it has been having such an energetic and upbeat student in our choir! Aiperi joined us the first day with a willingness to participate and be involved in all kinds of music-making. She is so eager to learn new styles, and has even signed up to sing a solo at the upcoming Section music contest! Her ever-present smile and infectious laugh brighten our afternoon rehearsals, and she has been a positive role model for all our singers. Thank you, Aiperi, for sharing your talent with us!‚Äù

Well done, #ChisholmBluestreaks! We are proud of you!

post_text:
The CHS REACH classes are collecting plastic grocery bags of any size/color to make "plarn" (plastic yarn) bedrolls. Do YOU have any grocery bags you could donate??

One of our REACH students recently saw a story about volunteer groups making these bedrolls from old plastic bags, and thought they'd be perfect to go with our care packages for those in need. Not only do they provide a clean, dry surface to sit or lie on, they also keep hundreds of plastic bags from reaching landfills!

Not many of our students know how to crochet, so they'll be learning a new skill as well! :)

Plastic bags can be dropped off at Room 207 at Chisholm High School. Thank you for your support! #ChisholmBluestreaks
